\end{thm}

\begin{rem}
    Since whenever $\card{U} \ge 3$, $R(U)$ is a group under addition, we need only check closure under multiplication to ensure that $R(U)$ is a ring.  
\end{rem}


The authors of \cite{buhler} then studied the case when $U$ is a group.  Specifically, they took the set of unit magnitude complex numbers $T$ (i.e., the unit circle) and considered it to be a group under complex multiplication.  Then they took the quotient of $T$ by $\{-1, +1\}$.  The result can be viewed as the top half of the unit circle.  By convention, whenever we use $U$, we will refer to $U \subseteq T/\{\pm 1\}$ where the elements are viewed as complex numbers.

\begin{thm}[\cite{buhler}]
    \label{groupring}
    Let $U$ be a subgroup of $T/\{-1, +1\}$ with $\card{U} \ge 3$.  Then, $R(U)$ is a ring.
\end{thm}

In their paper, Buhler et al.\ observed that $R(U)$ maybe be a ring even when $U$ is not a group.  They left the question of what properties $U$ must satisfy exactly for $R(U)$ to be a group open.

